Household-Level Education Dataset

Dataset Overview:

This dataset, education_final, aggregates individual-level education information from three sections of the household survey:

1. sec2a: General education (attendance, highest level, qualification, current schooling)

2. sec2b: Vocational and tertiary education (attendance, years, certificates, qualifications)

3. sec2c: Literacy, apprenticeship, and short training (reading/writing, calculation, literacy courses, apprenticeship, short courses)

The aggregation is performed at the household level using household ID (nh) and enumeration area (clust).

Data Processing Steps:

1. Variable Selection:

Only relevant variables were selected from each section.
Redundant or non-informative variables were dropped.

2. Missing Value Handling:

Numeric variables (years of schooling, certificates, apprenticeship duration):
-NAs replaced with 0 (indicating no participation).

Yes/No variables (attendance, literacy, apprenticeship):
-Converted to binary (1 = Yes, 0 = No) for aggregation.
-NAs treated as No in household-level aggregation.

3. Recoding
Yes/No variables at household level:
-Aggregated using max() across household members (if any member said Yes → household-level Yes).
-Converted back to survey coding: 1 = Yes, 2 = No.

Apprenticeship Status:
-1 = currently or previously an apprentice, 0 = never an apprentice.

Key Education attainment variables converted to numeric for regression/analysis:
-Highest education level (s2aq2_hh)
-Highest qualification (s2aq3_hh)
-Highest vocational certificate (s2bq3_hh)
-Highest tertiary qualification (s2bq8_hh)


4. Household level Aggregation
-Yes/No variables: max() across household members - household-level indicator if any member responded "Yes".
-Numeric variables: max() - captures highest level or years among household members.

5. Merging Sections
-Household-level datasets from sec2a, sec2b, and sec2c were merged using left_join on clust and nh.
-Households missing in sec2b (vocational/tertiary) assumed to have no participation.

Data Quality Checks
-No duplicates remain at the household level (clust + nh).
-All missing values for vocational/tertiary education filled with 0 (numeric) or 2 (No, Yes/No variables).
-Variable type conversions: Yes/No variables are binary (1 = Yes, 0 = No); ordinal variables numeric for modeling.
-Household coverage: All households included; missing individuals assumed to have zero or no participation.

Summary Highlights:
1. Total Households: nh:min=1 and max=25, clust: min=4002 and max=4999

2. Highest Education Levels (household max):
-s2aq2_hh (Highest level completed): peaks at maximum level in survey.
-s2bq6_hh (Years attended tertiary school): maximum 21 years. This value is part of the raw dataset and will be kept as is.
-s2cq8a_hh (Years in apprenticeship): maximum 39 years. This value is part of the raw dataset and will be kept as is.

3. Attendance Indicators:
-Majority of households have s2aq1_hh = 1 (ever attended school).
-Fewer households have vocational/tertiary attendance (s2bq1_hh and s2bq5_hh mostly 2 = No).

4. Literacy & Skills:
- Most households have at least one member who can read/write in English (s2cq1_hh, s2cq3_hh).
-Apprenticeship duration varies widely; peak values are retained as part of the raw survey data.

5. Key Patterns:
-Max aggregation ensures household captures highest attainment or participation among members.
-NA replacement strategy ensures no missing values in final dataset.
